<br>
<br>&bull; A memory system has to fit very large programs and still to provide fast access. 
<br>&bull; A hierarchical memory system can provide needed performance, based on the locality of reference. 
<br>&bull; Cache memory is an essential component of the memory system; it can be a single cache or organized as separate data and instruction caches. 
<br>&bull; Cache memories can be organized with direct mapping, set associative mapping, and associative mapping
<br>&bull; When a new block is brought into the cache, another one has to be replaced; in order to decide on which one to replace different strategies can be used: random, LRU, FIFO, LFU, etc. 
<br>&bull; In order to keep the content of the cache coherent with main memory, certain write strategies have to be used: write-through, write-through with buffered write, copy-back. 
<br>&bull; The address space seen by programs is a virtual one and is much larger than the available physical space. 
<br>&bull; Demand paging is based on the idea that only a part of the pages is in main memory at a certain moment; the OS loads pages into memory when needed. 
<br>&bull; The MMU translates a virtual address into a physical one; this is solved using the page table. 
<br>&bull; The page table itself is distributed along the memory hierarchy: TLB (cache), main memory, disk. 
